SIMPLE: everlasting
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Everlasting
<hw>Ever*last"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Lasting or enduring forever; existing or continuing without end;
immortal; eternal.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>Everlasting</xex> God.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Gen. xx1. 33.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Continuing indefinitely, or during a long period;
perpetual; sometimes used, colloquially, as a strong intensive; <as>as,
this <ex>everlasting</ex> nonsense</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will give to thee, and to thy seed after thee . . . the land of
Canaan, for an <qex>everlasting</qex> possession.</q> <rj><qau>Gen xvii.
8.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And heard thy <qex>everlasting</qex> yawn confess⟦br⟧
The pains and penalties of idleness.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Eternal; immortal, interminable; endless;
never-ending; infinite; unceasing; uninterrupted; continual;
unintermitted; incessant.</syn> <usage>-- <er>Everlasting</er>,
<er>Eternal</er>. <xex>Eternal</xex> denotes (when taken strictly)
without beginning or end of duration; <xex>everlasting</xex> is
sometimes used in our version of the Scriptures in the sense of
<xex>eternal</xex>, but in modern usage is confined to the future, and
implies no intermission as well as no end.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whether we shall meet again I know not;⟦br⟧
Therefore our <qex>everlasting</qex> farewell take;⟦br⟧
Forever, and forever farewell, Cassius.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Everlasting flower</b></col>. <cd>Sane as
<er>Everlasting</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 3.</cd> -- <col><b>Everlasting
pea</b></col>, <cd>an ornamental plant (<spn>Lathyrus latifolius</spn>)
related to the pea; -- so called because it is perennial.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Everlasting</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Everlasting
<hw>Ev`er*last"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Eternal
duration, past or future; eternity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From <qex>everlasting</qex> to <qex>everlasting</qex>, thou art
God.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. xc. 2.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>(With the definite article) The Eternal Being;
God.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A plant whose flowers may be dried
without losing their form or color, <as>as, the <styp>pearly
<ex>everlasting</ex></styp> (<spn>Anaphalis margaritacea</spn>), the
<stype>immortelle</stype> (<spn>Xeranthemum anuum</spn>) of the French,
the cudweeds, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A cloth fabric for shoes, etc. See
<er>Lasting</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Everlastingly</ent>⟦br⟧
